BLUETONGUE - EUROPE (48): BTV-8
*******************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Fri 26 Oct 2007
Source: The Scotsman [edited]
<http://business.scotsman.com/agriculture.cfm?id=1706152007>


Bluetongue [BT], the viral disease affecting sheep, cattle, goats,
and deer and which is spread by midges, continues to advance
throughout much of northern Europe.

As of last night [25 Oct 2007], there had been 52 confirmed cases,
chiefly in East Anglia, but there are ominous signs of the disease
spreading towards the Midlands and the south-west of England.
Movement restrictions are in place and the control zone is expanding
almost on a daily basis.

But the bad news for European Union farmers is that bluetongue has
been identified in southern Scandinavia and Poland [see commentary].
Denmark is perilously close to Scotland. The most recent estimate is
that over the past few months there have been over 25 000 confirmed
cases in northern Europe.

Cattle tend to recover relatively quickly from the infection, but the
mortality rate in sheep can be 70 percent. However, cattle and sheep
that survive the initial infection tend to suffer reduced growth and
lower levels of fertility.

There are at least 24 variations of bluetongue, some of which can be
restrained by vaccination. But there is no vaccine effective against
the strain BTV-8 -- now raging across much of northern Europe. That
must be addressed with the utmost urgency, according to Kim Heywood,
director of the National Beef Association (NBA).

She said: "We have no hesitation in calling on all the UK
governments, and the European Commission, to commit to immediate
vaccine development and to making sure there are enough doses on hand
to cover the entire population of vulnerable livestock before BTV-8
re-emerges next summer.

"Sadly, we understand that no moves have been made to kick-start this
process. The NBA has been advised by leading pharmaceutical companies
that up to 8 months is needed to secure a go-ahead, develop an
effective vaccine, acquire the licence, and organise distribution."

It is conceded that as many as 30 million doses would be required to
vaccinate the entire UK cattle herd with up to 15 million shots to
cover the sheep population, with further provision necessary for
booster injections. [The figures above, particularly in relation to
cattle, are excessive compared to data from other sources. According
to Defra (UK Department for Environment, Food, and Rural Affairs)
data, altogether there are about 10 million cattle in the UK: a
little over 2 million adult dairy cows, a little under 2 million
adult beef cows, and about 6 million younger animals. Even if each
animal is vaccinated twice, 30 million doses seem excessive. As to
sheep, Defra says their total number in the UK is about 36 million,
half of which are adult breeding animals. - Mod. AS]

The probability is that the EU's entire herd of 85 million cattle and
the flock of 90 million sheep will have to be vaccinated to forestall
the potential decimation of a sizeable proportion of the livestock
industry. The UK, bad as the current situation may be, could well be
in line for far greater problems next year [2008].

The evidence from France, Germany, Belgium, the Netherlands, and
Luxembourg suggests that bluetongue becomes decidedly more virulent
in the 2nd year after the initial outbreaks.

The worst-case scenario, unless there is a very severe winter to kill
off the midges, is that huge parts of the UK and mainland Europe will
be subject to stringent movement restrictions next summer and autumn
[2008] -- and there will be no compensation for farmers.

[Byline: Dan Buglass]

--
