[Obviously, the ADNS information from some of the affected countries
is not updated.

A map of the Dutch BT situation, as updated 22 Oct 2007, is available at
<http://www.vwa.nl/portal/page?_pageid=119,1640067&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL&p_document_id=108779&p_node_id=387989&p_mode=BROWSE>.
The map shows, in coloured dots, the bovine (violet) and sheep (red)
outbreaks, as well as the locations where vectors-traps are operated
(blue flags).

The French Ministry of Agriculture published an update on 24 Oct
2007, according to which 7259 cases (outbreaks?) of bluetongue have
been reported in France until the said date; no breakdown into
cattle, sheep, and goats was available. These French data have been
kindly provided by Susan Baekeland (<grolleyog@wanadoo.fr>), who is
gratefully acknowledged. The disagreement between these figures and
the figures in ADNS are in need of explanation.

In Germany, 15 404 "cases" (holdings?) had been reported until 19 Oct
2007. For additional information (in German) and a map, provided by
the Federal Friedrich-Loeffler Research Institute for Animal Health
on the isle of Riems, see
<http://www.fli.bund.de/253.html?&no_cache=1&tx_ttnews[tt_news]=297&cHash=0111265f06>.


Regarding the UK: as at 17:00 pm on 26 Oct 2007, there were 54
confirmed premises affected by bluetongue. - Mod. AS]
